. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and delayed phase <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a small, hypervascular-type hemangioma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow), with persistent enhancement on the delayed phase image. By comparison, another small hemangioma (arrowhead) has the more typical peripheral, nodular, interrupted enhancement pattern. <b>(c)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, both hemangiomas (arrow and arrowhead) have marked hyperintensity similar to that of fluid. <b>(d, e)</b> SSFP image <b>(d)</b> shows the hemangiomas as well-defined, hyperintense lesions (arrow and arrowhead), whereas a diffusion-weighted image <b>(e)</b> shows the lesions with marked hyperintensity related to T2 shine-through (arrow and arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Portal venous phase image obtained in a different patient shows a hemangioma (arrow). <b>(g)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed image obtained in the same patient as in <b>f</b>, the hemangioma is hypointense (arrow). One-hour to 3-hour delayed imaging with Gd-BOPTA is generally not helpful for hemangiomas because they can have a variable appearance that ranges from hypointensity to diffuse or central hyperintensity. <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows dilated, anastomosing, endothelium-lined blood-filled spaces with occasional fibrous septa (*). Note the adjacent normal liver parenchyma on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F1D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g01e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1527" aria-labelledby="F1E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1e.</b>  Small hemangiomas. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and delayed phase <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a small, hypervascular-type hemangioma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow), with persistent enhancement on the delayed phase image. By comparison, another small hemangioma (arrowhead) has the more typical peripheral, nodular, interrupted enhancement pattern. <b>(c)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, both hemangiomas (arrow and arrowhead) have marked hyperintensity similar to that of fluid. <b>(d, e)</b> SSFP image <b>(d)</b> shows the hemangiomas as well-defined, hyperintense lesions (arrow and arrowhead), whereas a diffusion-weighted image <b>(e)</b> shows the lesions with marked hyperintensity related to T2 shine-through (arrow and arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Portal venous phase image obtained in a different patient shows a hemangioma (arrow). <b>(g)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed image obtained in the same patient as in <b>f</b>, the hemangioma is hypointense (arrow). One-hour to 3-hour delayed imaging with Gd-BOPTA is generally not helpful for hemangiomas because they can have a variable appearance that ranges from hypointensity to diffuse or central hyperintensity. <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows dilated, anastomosing, endothelium-lined blood-filled spaces with occasional fibrous septa (*). Note the adjacent normal liver parenchyma on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F1E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g01f.jpeg" height="1800" width="1532" aria-labelledby="F1F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1f.</b>  Small hemangiomas. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and delayed phase <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a small, hypervascular-type hemangioma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow), with persistent enhancement on the delayed phase image. By comparison, another small hemangioma (arrowhead) has the more typical peripheral, nodular, interrupted enhancement pattern. <b>(c)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, both hemangiomas (arrow and arrowhead) have marked hyperintensity similar to that of fluid. <b>(d, e)</b> SSFP image <b>(d)</b> shows the hemangiomas as well-defined, hyperintense lesions (arrow and arrowhead), whereas a diffusion-weighted image <b>(e)</b> shows the lesions with marked hyperintensity related to T2 shine-through (arrow and arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Portal venous phase image obtained in a different patient shows a hemangioma (arrow). <b>(g)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed image obtained in the same patient as in <b>f</b>, the hemangioma is hypointense (arrow). One-hour to 3-hour delayed imaging with Gd-BOPTA is generally not helpful for hemangiomas because they can have a variable appearance that ranges from hypointensity to diffuse or central hyperintensity. <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows dilated, anastomosing, endothelium-lined blood-filled spaces with occasional fibrous septa (*). Note the adjacent normal liver parenchyma on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F1F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1G" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g01g.jpeg" height="1789" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1G" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1g.</b>  Small hemangiomas. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and delayed phase <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a small, hypervascular-type hemangioma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow), with persistent enhancement on the delayed phase image. By comparison, another small hemangioma (arrowhead) has the more typical peripheral, nodular, interrupted enhancement pattern. <b>(c)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, both hemangiomas (arrow and arrowhead) have marked hyperintensity similar to that of fluid. <b>(d, e)</b> SSFP image <b>(d)</b> shows the hemangiomas as well-defined, hyperintense lesions (arrow and arrowhead), whereas a diffusion-weighted image <b>(e)</b> shows the lesions with marked hyperintensity related to T2 shine-through (arrow and arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Portal venous phase image obtained in a different patient shows a hemangioma (arrow). <b>(g)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed image obtained in the same patient as in <b>f</b>, the hemangioma is hypointense (arrow). One-hour to 3-hour delayed imaging with Gd-BOPTA is generally not helpful for hemangiomas because they can have a variable appearance that ranges from hypointensity to diffuse or central hyperintensity. <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows dilated, anastomosing, endothelium-lined blood-filled spaces with occasional fibrous septa (*). Note the adjacent normal liver parenchyma on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F1G">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1H" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c01h.jpeg" height="876" width="1178" aria-labelledby="F1H" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1h.</b>  Small hemangiomas. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and delayed phase <b>(b)</b> T1-weighted MR images show a small, hypervascular-type hemangioma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow), with persistent enhancement on the delayed phase image. By comparison, another small hemangioma (arrowhead) has the more typical peripheral, nodular, interrupted enhancement pattern. <b>(c)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, both hemangiomas (arrow and arrowhead) have marked hyperintensity similar to that of fluid. <b>(d, e)</b> SSFP image <b>(d)</b> shows the hemangiomas as well-defined, hyperintense lesions (arrow and arrowhead), whereas a diffusion-weighted image <b>(e)</b> shows the lesions with marked hyperintensity related to T2 shine-through (arrow and arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Portal venous phase image obtained in a different patient shows a hemangioma (arrow). <b>(g)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed image obtained in the same patient as in <b>f</b>, the hemangioma is hypointense (arrow). One-hour to 3-hour delayed imaging with Gd-BOPTA is generally not helpful for hemangiomas because they can have a variable appearance that ranges from hypointensity to diffuse or central hyperintensity. <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows dilated, anastomosing, endothelium-lined blood-filled spaces with occasional fibrous septa (*). Note the adjacent normal liver parenchyma on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F1H">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1688" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02b.jpeg" height="1727" width="1620" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02c.jpeg" height="1656" width="1558" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1695" aria-labelledby="F2D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2d.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1714" aria-labelledby="F2E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2e.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02f.jpeg" height="1800" width="1740" aria-labelledby="F2F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2f.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2G" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g02g.jpeg" height="1800" width="1621" aria-labelledby="F2G" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2g.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2G">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2H" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c02h.jpeg" height="899" width="1101" aria-labelledby="F2H" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2h.</b>  FNH. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a homogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) with a hypoenhancing scar (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> On a delayed phase MR image, the mass (arrow) has “faded” (ie, has become isointense relative to adjacent liver), with delayed enhancement of the scar (arrowhead). <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(d)</b> MR images show the mass (arrow) with an intensity similar to that of the adjacent liver. The scar is hypointense on the T1-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and hyperintense on the T2-weighted image (arrowhead in <b>d</b>). <b>(e, f)</b> Arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed <b>(f)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass (arrow) that remains hyperintense relative to the liver, a finding that is consistent with FNH. <b>(g)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image obtained in a third patient shows how FNH can also have a peripheral ring-type, delayed enhancement pattern (arrow). <b>(h)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; Masson stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen shows benign hepatocytes with radiating fibrous septa, a few larger vessels, and shrunken bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F2H">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g03a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1701" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g03b.jpeg" height="1602" width="1511" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g03c.jpeg" height="1566" width="1484" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g03d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1549" aria-labelledby="F3D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3d.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g03e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1549" aria-labelledby="F3E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3e.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g03f.jpeg" height="1800" width="1554" aria-labelledby="F3F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3f.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3G" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c03g.jpeg" height="981" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3G" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3g.</b>  Hepatic adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a hypervascular mass in the periphery of the right lobe (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> T1-weighted MR images show the mass (arrow) with relatively lower signal intensity on the latter image, a finding that indicates the presence of intralesional fat and helps identify the mass as an adenoma rather than FNH. However, smaller adenomas uncomplicated by hemorrhage or fat may mimic FNH at imaging. <b>(d, e)</b> Postcontrast arterial phase <b>(d)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained in a different patient show a hypervascular mass in the right lobe (arrow) with subtle, mild hyperintensity on the diffusion-weighted image. The mass was occult with other sequences. <b>(f)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to normal liver. Fine-needle aspiration biopsy of the mass was performed because adenomas and a minority of FNHs (&lt;4%) can manifest in a similar fashion. <b>(g)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a biopsy specimen reveals bland hepatocytes without normal bile duct structures or fibrous septa, findings that confirm the diagnosis of hepatic adenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F3G">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g04a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1726" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  HCC in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) and two adjacent satellite nodules (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows all three lesions with washout, as well as a capsule with delayed enhancement (arrow and arrowheads). The lesions were predominantly T1 hypointense and mildly T2 hyperintense. <b>(c, d)</b> On SSFP <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(d)</b> images, the dominant mass (arrow) and the other two nodules (arrowheads) are mildly hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H–E stain) reveals well-differentiated HCC (*) with a rim of surrounding fibrous tissue (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g04b.jpeg" height="1291" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  HCC in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) and two adjacent satellite nodules (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows all three lesions with washout, as well as a capsule with delayed enhancement (arrow and arrowheads). The lesions were predominantly T1 hypointense and mildly T2 hyperintense. <b>(c, d)</b> On SSFP <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(d)</b> images, the dominant mass (arrow) and the other two nodules (arrowheads) are mildly hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H–E stain) reveals well-differentiated HCC (*) with a rim of surrounding fibrous tissue (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g04c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  HCC in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) and two adjacent satellite nodules (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows all three lesions with washout, as well as a capsule with delayed enhancement (arrow and arrowheads). The lesions were predominantly T1 hypointense and mildly T2 hyperintense. <b>(c, d)</b> On SSFP <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(d)</b> images, the dominant mass (arrow) and the other two nodules (arrowheads) are mildly hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H–E stain) reveals well-differentiated HCC (*) with a rim of surrounding fibrous tissue (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g04d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1786" aria-labelledby="F4D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4d.</b>  HCC in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) and two adjacent satellite nodules (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows all three lesions with washout, as well as a capsule with delayed enhancement (arrow and arrowheads). The lesions were predominantly T1 hypointense and mildly T2 hyperintense. <b>(c, d)</b> On SSFP <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(d)</b> images, the dominant mass (arrow) and the other two nodules (arrowheads) are mildly hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H–E stain) reveals well-differentiated HCC (*) with a rim of surrounding fibrous tissue (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F4D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c04e.jpeg" height="871" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4e.</b>  HCC in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, hypervascular mass (arrow) and two adjacent satellite nodules (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows all three lesions with washout, as well as a capsule with delayed enhancement (arrow and arrowheads). The lesions were predominantly T1 hypointense and mildly T2 hyperintense. <b>(c, d)</b> On SSFP <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted <b>(d)</b> images, the dominant mass (arrow) and the other two nodules (arrowheads) are mildly hyperintense. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H–E stain) reveals well-differentiated HCC (*) with a rim of surrounding fibrous tissue (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F4E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1549" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  NRH in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple (at least eight) small, hypervascular nodules (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> On T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(c)</b> images, the nodules (arrows) are iso- to hyperintense and iso- to hypointense, respectively. The lesions were isointense with SSFP and diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(d)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image shows NRH (arrows) with the typical iso- to hyperintensity, similar to that of FNH. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen reveals benign hepatocytes with bile ducts and no malignant cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1549" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  NRH in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple (at least eight) small, hypervascular nodules (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> On T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(c)</b> images, the nodules (arrows) are iso- to hyperintense and iso- to hypointense, respectively. The lesions were isointense with SSFP and diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(d)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image shows NRH (arrows) with the typical iso- to hyperintensity, similar to that of FNH. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen reveals benign hepatocytes with bile ducts and no malignant cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g05c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1554" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  NRH in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple (at least eight) small, hypervascular nodules (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> On T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(c)</b> images, the nodules (arrows) are iso- to hyperintense and iso- to hypointense, respectively. The lesions were isointense with SSFP and diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(d)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image shows NRH (arrows) with the typical iso- to hyperintensity, similar to that of FNH. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen reveals benign hepatocytes with bile ducts and no malignant cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g05d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1593" aria-labelledby="F5D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5d.</b>  NRH in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple (at least eight) small, hypervascular nodules (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> On T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(c)</b> images, the nodules (arrows) are iso- to hyperintense and iso- to hypointense, respectively. The lesions were isointense with SSFP and diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(d)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image shows NRH (arrows) with the typical iso- to hyperintensity, similar to that of FNH. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen reveals benign hepatocytes with bile ducts and no malignant cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F5D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c05e.jpeg" height="966" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F5E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5e.</b>  NRH in a patient with Budd-Chiari syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple (at least eight) small, hypervascular nodules (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> On T1-weighted <b>(b)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(c)</b> images, the nodules (arrows) are iso- to hyperintense and iso- to hypointense, respectively. The lesions were isointense with SSFP and diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(d)</b> Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed MR image shows NRH (arrows) with the typical iso- to hyperintensity, similar to that of FNH. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H–E stain) of a core needle biopsy specimen reveals benign hepatocytes with bile ducts and no malignant cells.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F5E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g06a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1647" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (insulinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrow) with surrounding hypointensity (arrowheads). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> images show the mass surrounded by an area of mild hyperintensity (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and hypointensity (arrowheads in <b>c</b>), respectively, findings that confirm the presence of perilesional fat. <b>(d)</b> SSFP image shows hypervascular metastases with marked hyperintensity that mimics the signal intensity of cysts or hemangiomas. Because SSFP sequences are performed with a short echo time (1.2 msec), perilesional hypointensity (arrowheads) similar to that depicted at opposed-phase T1-weighted imaging is again seen (cf <b>c</b>). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H–E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen reveals rare clusters of loosely cohesive, cytologically low-grade cells with round nuclei that stain strongly for synaptophysin, a neuroendocrine marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g06b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1618" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (insulinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrow) with surrounding hypointensity (arrowheads). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> images show the mass surrounded by an area of mild hyperintensity (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and hypointensity (arrowheads in <b>c</b>), respectively, findings that confirm the presence of perilesional fat. <b>(d)</b> SSFP image shows hypervascular metastases with marked hyperintensity that mimics the signal intensity of cysts or hemangiomas. Because SSFP sequences are performed with a short echo time (1.2 msec), perilesional hypointensity (arrowheads) similar to that depicted at opposed-phase T1-weighted imaging is again seen (cf <b>c</b>). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H–E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen reveals rare clusters of loosely cohesive, cytologically low-grade cells with round nuclei that stain strongly for synaptophysin, a neuroendocrine marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g06c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1626" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (insulinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrow) with surrounding hypointensity (arrowheads). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> images show the mass surrounded by an area of mild hyperintensity (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and hypointensity (arrowheads in <b>c</b>), respectively, findings that confirm the presence of perilesional fat. <b>(d)</b> SSFP image shows hypervascular metastases with marked hyperintensity that mimics the signal intensity of cysts or hemangiomas. Because SSFP sequences are performed with a short echo time (1.2 msec), perilesional hypointensity (arrowheads) similar to that depicted at opposed-phase T1-weighted imaging is again seen (cf <b>c</b>). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H–E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen reveals rare clusters of loosely cohesive, cytologically low-grade cells with round nuclei that stain strongly for synaptophysin, a neuroendocrine marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g06d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1677" aria-labelledby="F6D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6d.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (insulinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrow) with surrounding hypointensity (arrowheads). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> images show the mass surrounded by an area of mild hyperintensity (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and hypointensity (arrowheads in <b>c</b>), respectively, findings that confirm the presence of perilesional fat. <b>(d)</b> SSFP image shows hypervascular metastases with marked hyperintensity that mimics the signal intensity of cysts or hemangiomas. Because SSFP sequences are performed with a short echo time (1.2 msec), perilesional hypointensity (arrowheads) similar to that depicted at opposed-phase T1-weighted imaging is again seen (cf <b>c</b>). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H–E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen reveals rare clusters of loosely cohesive, cytologically low-grade cells with round nuclei that stain strongly for synaptophysin, a neuroendocrine marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F6D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c06e.jpeg" height="911" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6e.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (insulinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrow) with surrounding hypointensity (arrowheads). <b>(b, c)</b> In-phase <b>(b)</b> and opposed-phase <b>(c)</b> images show the mass surrounded by an area of mild hyperintensity (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and hypointensity (arrowheads in <b>c</b>), respectively, findings that confirm the presence of perilesional fat. <b>(d)</b> SSFP image shows hypervascular metastases with marked hyperintensity that mimics the signal intensity of cysts or hemangiomas. Because SSFP sequences are performed with a short echo time (1.2 msec), perilesional hypointensity (arrowheads) similar to that depicted at opposed-phase T1-weighted imaging is again seen (cf <b>c</b>). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H–E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen reveals rare clusters of loosely cohesive, cytologically low-grade cells with round nuclei that stain strongly for synaptophysin, a neuroendocrine marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F6E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g07a.jpeg" height="1177" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (melanoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple hypervascular masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Diffusion-weighted image better delineates the masses (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On a precontrast T1-weighted image, two of the masses are hyperintense (arrows), a finding that suggests hemorrhage or melanin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification × 40; H-E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen helps confirm the presence of melanoma metastases (*). Photomicrograph obtained at a higher magnification (× 600) with H-E stain (inset) shows an epithelioid tumor with the dusty brown cytoplasmic pigment, prominent nucleoli, and intranuclear vacuolation typical of melanoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g07b.jpeg" height="1213" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (melanoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple hypervascular masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Diffusion-weighted image better delineates the masses (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On a precontrast T1-weighted image, two of the masses are hyperintense (arrows), a finding that suggests hemorrhage or melanin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification × 40; H-E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen helps confirm the presence of melanoma metastases (*). Photomicrograph obtained at a higher magnification (× 600) with H-E stain (inset) shows an epithelioid tumor with the dusty brown cytoplasmic pigment, prominent nucleoli, and intranuclear vacuolation typical of melanoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g07c.jpeg" height="1146" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (melanoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple hypervascular masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Diffusion-weighted image better delineates the masses (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On a precontrast T1-weighted image, two of the masses are hyperintense (arrows), a finding that suggests hemorrhage or melanin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification × 40; H-E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen helps confirm the presence of melanoma metastases (*). Photomicrograph obtained at a higher magnification (× 600) with H-E stain (inset) shows an epithelioid tumor with the dusty brown cytoplasmic pigment, prominent nucleoli, and intranuclear vacuolation typical of melanoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c07d.jpeg" height="865" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F7D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7d.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (melanoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple hypervascular masses (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Diffusion-weighted image better delineates the masses (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On a precontrast T1-weighted image, two of the masses are hyperintense (arrows), a finding that suggests hemorrhage or melanin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification × 40; H-E stain) of a fine-needle aspiration biopsy specimen helps confirm the presence of melanoma metastases (*). Photomicrograph obtained at a higher magnification (× 600) with H-E stain (inset) shows an epithelioid tumor with the dusty brown cytoplasmic pigment, prominent nucleoli, and intranuclear vacuolation typical of melanoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F7D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g08a.jpeg" height="1218" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (rectal adenocarcinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, peripherally hypervascular mass (arrow) in the left hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed T1-weighted MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to the liver. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H-E stain) shows multiple foci of malignant adenocarcinoma (*) in fibrous stroma that replaces the hepatic parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g08b.jpeg" height="1218" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (rectal adenocarcinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, peripherally hypervascular mass (arrow) in the left hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed T1-weighted MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to the liver. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H-E stain) shows multiple foci of malignant adenocarcinoma (*) in fibrous stroma that replaces the hepatic parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12c08c.jpeg" height="606" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Hypervascular metastases (rectal adenocarcinoma). <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a heterogeneous, peripherally hypervascular mass (arrow) in the left hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> On a Gd-BOPTA–enhanced 1-hour delayed T1-weighted MR image, the mass (arrow) is hypointense relative to the liver. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 40; H-E stain) shows multiple foci of malignant adenocarcinoma (*) in fibrous stroma that replaces the hepatic parenchyma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g09a.jpeg" height="1184" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Treated metastases mimicking hemangiomas in a patient who was undergoing chemotherapy for metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple lesions, two of which are hypervascular (arrows) and two hypovascular (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows persistent enhancement of the hypervascular lesions (arrows) and peripheral nodular enhancement of the hypovascular lesions (arrowheads), findings that incorrectly suggest hemangiomas. <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows marked hyperintensity of the lesions (arrows and arrowheads), a finding that again incorrectly suggests hemangiomas. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up T2-weighted MR image obtained 7 months later shows dramatic improvement in the burden of metastatic disease (arrow and arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g09b.jpeg" height="1185" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Treated metastases mimicking hemangiomas in a patient who was undergoing chemotherapy for metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple lesions, two of which are hypervascular (arrows) and two hypovascular (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows persistent enhancement of the hypervascular lesions (arrows) and peripheral nodular enhancement of the hypovascular lesions (arrowheads), findings that incorrectly suggest hemangiomas. <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows marked hyperintensity of the lesions (arrows and arrowheads), a finding that again incorrectly suggests hemangiomas. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up T2-weighted MR image obtained 7 months later shows dramatic improvement in the burden of metastatic disease (arrow and arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g09c.jpeg" height="1182" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Treated metastases mimicking hemangiomas in a patient who was undergoing chemotherapy for metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple lesions, two of which are hypervascular (arrows) and two hypovascular (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows persistent enhancement of the hypervascular lesions (arrows) and peripheral nodular enhancement of the hypovascular lesions (arrowheads), findings that incorrectly suggest hemangiomas. <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows marked hyperintensity of the lesions (arrows and arrowheads), a finding that again incorrectly suggests hemangiomas. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up T2-weighted MR image obtained 7 months later shows dramatic improvement in the burden of metastatic disease (arrow and arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g09d.jpeg" height="1182" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9d.</b>  Treated metastases mimicking hemangiomas in a patient who was undergoing chemotherapy for metastatic breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows multiple lesions, two of which are hypervascular (arrows) and two hypovascular (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Portal venous phase image shows persistent enhancement of the hypervascular lesions (arrows) and peripheral nodular enhancement of the hypovascular lesions (arrowheads), findings that incorrectly suggest hemangiomas. <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows marked hyperintensity of the lesions (arrows and arrowheads), a finding that again incorrectly suggests hemangiomas. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up T2-weighted MR image obtained 7 months later shows dramatic improvement in the burden of metastatic disease (arrow and arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F9D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g10a.jpeg" height="1463" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  THID in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular lesion in the left hepatic lobe (arrow). The lesion faded to become isoenhancing relative to normal liver on portal venous phase and delayed phase images and was not visible with T1-weighted, T2-weighted, SSFP, or diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up MR image obtained 3 months later does not depict the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12g10b.jpeg" height="1461" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  THID in a cirrhotic patient. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase T1-weighted MR image shows a small, hypervascular lesion in the left hepatic lobe (arrow). The lesion faded to become isoenhancing relative to normal liver on portal venous phase and delayed phase images and was not visible with T1-weighted, T2-weighted, SSFP, or diffusion-weighted sequences. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up MR image obtained 3 months later does not depict the lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12l11x.jpeg" height="559" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11.</b>  Chart illustrates a decision algorithm that can be helpful in evaluating hypervascular liver lesions. <i>AVM</i> = arteriovenous malformation, <i>Hetero</i> = heterogeneous.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085123&amp;id=F11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 1.</b> <b>MR Signal Intensity Characteristics of Hypervascular Liver Masses before and after Administration</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12t01x.jpeg" height="578" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote"><div role="paragraph">Note.—Arrows indicate increased (“up” arrow) or decreased (“down” arrow) signal intensity or enhancement relative to the surrounding normal liver. Arrows in parentheses indicate increased or decreased signal intensity or enhancement in an area of central scarring. Double up arrows indicate marked hyperintensity. Iso = isointense or isoenhancing.</div><div role="paragraph">*Heterogeneous.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>†</sup>Lesser degree of change in signal intensity or enhancement.</div></div></div></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T2" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 2.</b> <b>SSFP and Diffusion-weighted Imaging Protocols</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085123/asset/images/g09mr12t02x.jpeg" height="1578" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T2" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote">Note.—ASSET = parallel imaging, FIESTA = fast imaging employing steady-state acquisition, NA = not applicable.</div></div></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Semelka</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">RC</span></span>, Armao DM, Elias J Jr, Huda W. Imaging strategies to reduce the risk of radiation in CT studies, including selective substitution with MRI. <em>J Magn Reson Imaging</em>2007; 25(5): 900–909.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/jmri.20895">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17457809/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=J+Magn+Reson+Imaging&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;pages=900&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fjmri.20895&amp;pmid=17457809">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Semelka</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">RC</span></span>, Martin DR, Balci C, Lance T. Focal liver lesions: comparison of dual-phase CT and multisequence multiplanar MR imaging including dynamic gadolinium enhancement. <em>J Magn Reson Imaging</em>2001; 13(3): 397–401.</div><div clas